 ventures llc more info more info profile biography gary l cowger is chairman and ceo of glc ventures llc a management consultancy on business manufacturing and technology strategy  he is also chairman of the board of trustees at kettering university and serves on the board of directors of delphi corporation  mr cowger received his bachelor’s degree in industrial engineering at general motors institute now kettering university in  his master’s degree in management at the massachusetts institute of technology in  and he holds an honorary doctorate of humane letters from lindenwood college  and an honorary doctor of engineering from kettering university  mr cowgers career at general motors spanned  years  he served in various capacities at gm and at his retirement was group vice president of global manufacturing and labor relations  in this position he was responsible for directing all of gm’s manufacturing manufacturing engineering and labor relations activities worldwide and was a member of the automotive strategy board and the automotive product board  he was instrumental in leading the development of several manufacturing technologies including the use of mathbased tools along with the adoption of synchronous and lean manufacturing at gm mr cowger was elected to the national academy of engineering for his contributions to the gm global manufacturing system which dramatically improved flexibility quality and productivity in automotive manufacturing  he received the m eugene merchant manufacturing medal from the american society of mechanical engineers and the society of manufacturing engineers in   mr cowger was named a fellow of stanford university in  becoming only the fifth recipient of this honor in  years  he was selected automotive industries’ executive of the year   he is the recipient of the society of automotive engineers’ manufacturing leadership award  and the shienming wu foundation’s wu manufacturing leadership award  read more read less share print nae website  workshop agenda xs sm md lg × login keep me signed in create new account toggle navigation giving about contact media room follow us on nae login members only click here to login if youre an nae member login forgot username or password recover your account information reset password nonnae members login keep me signed in membership inquiries  naemembershipofficenaeedu home activities overview projects manufacturing design and innovation events committee meetings making value workshop workshop agenda manufacturing design and innovation overview projects  events  workshop agenda featured resources making value integrating manufacturing design and innovation to thrive in the changing global economy manufacturing is in a period of dramatic transformation but in the united states public and political dialogue is simplistically focused almost entirely on the movement of certain manufacturing jobs overseas to lowwage countries the nae workshop on making value integrating manufacturing design and innovation to thrive in the changing global economy was held june   in washington dc june    am breakfast  am –  am registration  am –  am welcome and opening remarks more charles m vest national academy of engineering  am audio recording opening keynote more curtis r carlson sri international  am capital room audio recording jonathan dordick power point the changing nature of manufacturing design and innovation cuttingedge technological developments and business models have the potential to revolutionize manufacturing design and innovation in the united states and globally innovations in nanotechnology biotechnology and robotics are enabling new production processes that can generate entirely novel types of products advances in information technology are facilitating a closer integration of the customer into business processes than ever before what lies ahead at the intersection of manufacturing design and innovation how is the increased focus on the entire customer experience influencing products production and business models how will americans be affected by these changes more moderator louis rassey mckinsey  company panelist jonathan j rubinstein palm inc panelist jonathan dordick center for biotechnology  interdisciplinary studies rensselaer polytechnic institute  am break  am capital room audio recording digitization productivity and jobs power point the future of work us manufacturing employment has decreased from more than  million in  to less than  million today although these numbers imply a decline of job opportunities in manufacturing the reality of how work is transforming on and off the factory floor is far from simple how are developments in technology and business models changing the nature of work in manufacturing design and innovation what lies ahead in a world of increasing automation intelligent products agile production and customerexperiencedriven manufacturing what types and scale of job opportunities are emerging how can the workforce prepare for this future more moderator laura steinberg syracuse university panelist gary l cowger glc ventures llc panelist erik brynjolfsson mit  am capital room audio recording building the ecosystem to support entrepreneurship power point building the ecosystem for the future of manufacturing design and innovation in recent years the concept of a “manufacturing ecosystem” has emerged to describe the interconnected system of individual companies both drawing on and contributing to shared resources including workforce talent infrastructure and networks of suppliers and partners what is the state of the manufacturing design and innovation ecosystem how is this ecosystem changing in response to increased global integration emerging technologies and transforming business models what are the weakest links in the valuechains within this ecosystem where are the opportunities to improve the value that the nation receives from the global ecosystem of manufacturing design and innovation more moderator willy c shih harvard business school panelist gp bud peterson georgia institute of technology panelist dawn white accio energy panelist kaigham ken j gabriel defense advanced research projects agency  pm audio recording luncheon keynote manufacturing for sustainability power point luncheon more jay golden duke center for sustainability  commerce  pm –  pm portrait gallery room group a the relationship of making things and making value  pm –  pm smithsonian room group b productivity innovation and business practices what are exemplary business practices of companies that enable productivity and innovation what technologies tools or programs could help what is the impact of lowperforming companies on the ability to advance the frontier of mdi and capture value in the united states what are the barriers and opportunities to improve the productivity of lowperforming companies  pm –  pm capital room group c the role of geography in creating and capturing value how does the global distribution of mdi activities affect the ability to create and capture value how important are clusters of production design and research facilities how does this importance vary across different types of industries  pm –  pm lincoln memorial room group d enabling the workforce for the future of mdi what will be needed to transition the workforce for the future of mdi what are major barriers and opportunities to enable the workforce with the knowledge and skills needed for this future what tools or programs could facilitate this transition  pm –  pm jefferson monument room group e building the institutional structure for mdi what is the impact of ip rights financing permitting and other aspects of the institutional structure on the ability to capture value in the united states where are the weakest links to what extent do these aspects affect location decisions of production design and research facilities what are other countries’ strategies and would they work in the united s